<section xml:id="sec_cont_func_summ">
  <title>Summary</title>
  <p>
    Important ideas that we discussed in this section include the following.
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>(X,d_X)</m> and <m>(Y, d_Y)</m> be metric spaces.
          A function <m>f:X \to Y</m> is continuous at <m>a \in X</m> if,
          given any <m>\epsilon > 0</m>,
          there exists a <m>\delta > 0</m> so that
          <m>d_X(x,a)\lt \delta</m> implies <m>d_Y(f(x), f(a)) \lt \epsilon</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>(X,d_X)</m> and <m>(Y, d_Y)</m> be metric spaces.
          A function <m>f:X \to Y</m> is continuous if <m>f</m> is continuous at every point in <m>X</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</section>